# Mobile Responsive Design Standards

Standards for implementing mobile-responsive design patterns based on learnings from mobile navbar implementation.

<rule>
name: mobile_responsive_design
description: Standards for mobile-responsive design implementation
filters:
  - type: file_extension
    pattern: "\\.(html|css|js)$"
  - type: content
    pattern: "(navbar|navigation|header|mobile|responsive)"

actions:
  - type: suggest
    message: |
      ## Mobile Responsive Design Standards

      ### 1. Mobile-First Approach
      - Start with mobile design (≤600px) and scale up to desktop
      - Use progressive enhancement for desktop features
      - Test on actual mobile devices, not just browser dev tools

      ### 2. Breakpoint Strategy
      ```css
      /* Mobile-first approach */
      .component { /* Mobile styles */ }
      
      @media (min-width: 600px) {
        .component { /* Desktop styles */ }
      }
      ```

      ### 3. Touch-Friendly Design
      - Minimum touch target size: 44px × 44px
      - Adequate spacing between interactive elements
      - Consider thumb reach zones for mobile navigation

      ### 4. Navigation Patterns
      - Use hamburger menu for mobile navigation (≤600px)
      - Maintain traditional navbar for desktop (≥600px)
      - Ensure navigation is context-aware (logged-in vs logged-out)

      ### 5. Performance Considerations
      - Minimize CSS and JavaScript for mobile
      - Use efficient animations (CSS transforms over layout changes)
      - Optimize images and assets for mobile bandwidth

examples:
  - input: |
      /* Bad: Desktop-first approach */
      .navbar { display: flex; }
      @media (max-width: 600px) {
        .navbar { display: none; }
      }

      /* Good: Mobile-first approach */
      .navbar { display: none; }
      @media (min-width: 600px) {
        .navbar { display: flex; }
      }
    output: "Use mobile-first responsive design approach"

  - input: |
      /* Bad: Small touch targets */
      .nav-item { padding: 5px; }

      /* Good: Touch-friendly targets */
      .nav-item { 
        padding: 12px 16px;
        min-height: 44px;
        min-width: 44px;
      }
    output: "Ensure touch targets meet minimum 44px size requirement"

metadata:
  priority: high
  version: 1.0
  tags: ["mobile", "responsive", "design", "ux"]
</rule>
description:
globs:
alwaysApply: false
---
